				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">UniCredit Profit Jumps as Loan Losses Fall</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Jack Ewing			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-11-11T15:30:50+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 11, 2014 10:30 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 11, 2014 10:30 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/11/11/profit-jumps-at-unicredit-as-losses-from-bad-loans-decline/" data-title="UniCredit Profit Jumps as Loan Losses Fall" data-description="UniCredit&#039;s earnings report offers more evidence that it is healthy enough to provide badly needed loans to Italian businesses and individuals. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/12/business/dbpix-unicredit/dbpix-unicredit-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/12/business/dbpix-unicredit/dbpix-unicredit-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/12/business/dbpix-unicredit/dbpix-unicredit-blog480.jpg" id="100000003228545" width="480" height="316" alt="UniCredit&#039;s chief said the bank was close to achieving its target of a profit of â¬2 billion for the year."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="316"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">UniCredit's chief said the bank was close to achieving its target of a profit of â¬2 billion for the year.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Stefano Rellandini/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.unicreditgroup.eu/en/pressandmedia/pressreleases-price-sensitive/2014/unicredit--risultati-di-gruppo-3trim-2014.html">Earnings release</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">UniCredit said on Tuesday that net profit more than tripled in the third quarter as the Italian bank booked lower losses related to doubtful loans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Net profit rose to 722 million euros, or $900 million, from â¬204 million in the period a year earlier, <a href="https://www.unicreditgroup.eu/en/pressandmedia/pressreleases-price-sensitive/2014/unicredit--risultati-di-gruppo-3trim-2014.html">UniCredit said</a>. The bank reduced the amount of money it set aside to cover bad loans by almost half, to â¬754 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The profit was more than analysts had expected and marked a continuation of UniCreditâs recovery from the effects of the financial crisis and a prolonged downturn in Italy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Federico Ghizzoni, chief executive of UniCredit, said that while the bankâs home market remains difficult there are tentative signs that demand for loans could start to recover, in part because of cheap financing provided by the European Central Bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe see Italy recovering,â Mr. Ghizzoni said during a conference call with analysts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">UniCredit, Italyâs largest lender, said it had also benefited from a recovery in demand for loans within Italy; profit from its subsidiaries in Poland and other East European countries; and better earnings at the investment banking unit.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The profit report is a good sign for the Italian economy, which is hampered by a credit problem. As a group, Italian banks are among Europeâs most troubled. Nine of 15 Italian lenders failed a European Central Bank review last month of their ability to withstand a crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">UniCredit passed the E.C.B. review easily, however, and the earnings report on Tuesday offered more evidence that it was healthy enough to provide badly needed loans to Italian businesses and individuals.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Ghizzoni said the bank was close to achieving its target of a profit of â¬2 billion for the year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe are pleased with this positive trend, despite a still difficult macroeconomic context,â Mr. Ghizzoni said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Revenue for the quarter slipped 2 percent, to â¬5.6 billion, UniCredit said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The bank said it had borrowed â¬7.8 billion in cheap four-year loans offered by the European Central Bank as part of a program to encourage commercial banks to lend more to small businesses and individuals. UniCredit said it planned to borrow more money from the E.C.B. in December.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That will probably be welcome news to the E.C.B. Fewer banks than expected have taken advantage of the loan program despite an ultralow interest rate of 0.15 percent, fixed for four years. UniCreditâs use of the E.C.B. money suggests that the program is attractive at least to commercial banks in the most troubled countries.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even Russia continues to be profitable for UniCredit, which is one of the European banks most active there, Mr. Ghizzoni said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe performance of the Russian bank is extremely encouraging and the bank is very sound,â he said. While he is paying close attention to tension with the West over Ukraine, Mr. Ghizzoni said, âI am not overly concerned.â</p>
	</div>
